window.docContents[6].resolve({"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Fractional-ideals-and-the-class-group/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Fractional-ideals-and-the-class-group--Fractional-Ideals":{"contents":"Let  be a domain with fraction field . A fractional ideal of  is an\n-submodule  for which there exists a nonzero  with  — that is, an \"ideal with denominators\". Ordinary ideals are the integral\nfractional ideals; products and (for a Dedekind domain) inverses of fractional ideals are\nagain fractional ideals.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Algebraic Number Theory\u0009Fractional ideals and the class group","header":"3.3.1. Fractional Ideals","id":"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Fractional-ideals-and-the-class-group/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Fractional-ideals-and-the-class-group--Fractional-Ideals"},"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Algebraic-and-transcendental-numbers/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Algebraic-and-transcendental-numbers--Liouville___s-Theorem-on-Transcendence":{"contents":"(Liouville's theorem.) Every Liouville number () is transcendental over\n ().\n\nSuppose for contradiction that the Liouville number  is algebraic, the root of a nonzero\n of degree . The heart is exists_pos_real_of_irrational_root, which (since\n is irrational, ) produces a constant  with\n\nThat lemma combines three inputs:  has finitely many roots, so there is a closed ball around \nin which  is its only root (exists_closedBall_inter_eq_singleton_of_discrete);  is Lipschitz\nthere because its derivative is bounded on a compact interval, via the Mean Value Theorem\n(Convex.norm_image_sub_le_of_norm_deriv_le); and the integrality bound —  is a\nnonzero integer, hence  in absolute value (one_le_pow_mul_abs_eval_div) — which would fail\nonly if  were a rational root, excluded by irrationality. Now use the Archimedean property to\npick  with  (pow_unbounded_of_one_lt), and apply the Liouville property\n() at exponent  to obtain  with\n. Chaining the two bounds gives\n, contradicting lt_irrefl. This is the exact\ncounterpoint to Dirichlet's theorem (): an algebraic irrational of degree\n cannot be approximated past order .\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Diophantine Equations and Transcendence\u0009Algebraic and transcendental numbers","header":"9.6.4. Liouville's Theorem on Transcendence","id":"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Algebraic-and-transcendental-numbers/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Algebraic-and-transcendental-numbers--Liouville___s-Theorem-on-Transcendence"},"/Elementary-Number-Theory/Divisibility___-gcd___-and-the-fundamental-theorem-of-arithmetic/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elementary-Number-Theory--Divisibility___-gcd___-and-the-fundamental-theorem-of-arithmetic--The-Prime-Factorization-Function":{"contents":"For a positive integer , the factorization of  is the finitely-supported function  whose support is the set of prime divisors of  and which sends each prime  to its multiplicity , the -adic valuation of  — equivalently the number of times  occurs in the list of prime factors of .\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Elementary Number Theory\u0009Divisibility, gcd, and the fundamental theorem of arithmetic","header":"1.1.4. The Prime Factorization Function","id":"/Elementary-Number-Theory/Divisibility___-gcd___-and-the-fundamental-theorem-of-arithmetic/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elementary-Number-Theory--Divisibility___-gcd___-and-the-fundamental-theorem-of-arithmetic--The-Prime-Factorization-Function"},"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/The-adic-spectrum/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--The-adic-spectrum--Quasi-compactness-of-the-adic-spectrum":{"contents":"(Quasi-compactness of the adic spectrum.) For a Tate affinoid ring  with\npseudo-uniformiser, the adic spectrum  () is\nquasi-compact.\nFormalised in Adic-Spaces: isCompact_spa_of_tate_pseudouniformizer, instCompactSpace_spa_of_tate_pseudouniformizer — sorry-free.\n\nUnlike , the set  is not in general closed in\n, so the naive \"closed-in-compact\" route fails. Instead the project embeds\n into the compact Hausdorff space  via the Huber\nindicator ; the image of\n is closed there (ValuationSpectrumCompact). Each integrality condition\n for  is a clopen coordinate condition, so \nis the intersection of the closed image with clopen sets, hence closed and therefore compact;\ntransporting back through the embedding gives quasi-compactness of . The Tate\npseudo-uniformiser is what supplies the discrete-on-value-groups input the embedding needs.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009p-adic and Adic Spaces\u0009The adic spectrum","header":"5.12.6. Quasi-compactness of the adic spectrum","id":"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/The-adic-spectrum/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--The-adic-spectrum--Quasi-compactness-of-the-adic-spectrum"}});